                     <interp inst="def2-1458-18390408" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1458-18390408" type="surname" value="BELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1458-18390408" type="given" value="JEMIMA"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JEMIMA BELL</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18390408-1458-offence-2" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18390408-1458-offence-2" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18390408-1458-offence-2" type="offenceSubcategory" value="receiving"></interp>, for feloniously receiving the same, well knowing them to have been stolen; against the Statute,</rs>
                  <hi rend="italic">&amp;c.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390408-name-1658" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1658" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1658" type="surname" value="ATKINSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1658" type="given" value="MARTIN"></interp>MARTIN ATKINSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep a linen-drapery warehouse, in the West<lb></lb>minster-road. James Bell had been in my service for about eight months, up to March last, and I had known him for some years—I had some sus<lb></lb>picion, and directed a shopman to watch him—on the evening of the 7th of March my shopman communicated something to me, and the prisoner was called back, as he was about leaving my premises—he followed me into my</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183904080241"></xptr>
               <p>counting-house—I said to him, "Give me back my property"—he pulled a piece of huckaback out of his pocket, and gave it to me—it was my pro<lb></lb>perty—he said, "I hope you will for give roe, sir, for the sake of my family, and if you will allow me to go home, I will return to-morrow morning, and then do what you like"—I gave him into custody—I have since seen five black silk handkerchiefs, and a piece of lawn, which are mine—these are them—(<hi rend="italic">examining them</hi>)—I had missed the handkerchiefs from my shop, and made an outcry about them—I was present at the examination of the pri<lb></lb>soners, they made a statement which was taken down, and as I was leaving the Court, they went up to sign it—this signature to this examination is the hand-writing of James Bell—I do not know the hand-writing of the other prisoner, who is his daughter.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I believe this man has been in much better life than he is now? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He was in business for himself about thirteen years back—he has a wife, and I think four children—when he came first to me he had 25<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a-week, as I had younger hands, who took more money than he did, I intimated that he might leave me, but at be said he wished I would keep him till the turn of the year, I said I would give him 20<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a-week, which I did—he boarded in my house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390408-name-1659" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1659" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1659" type="surname" value="WORLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1659" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE WORLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of Messrs. Walmsley, pawn-brokers. I produce five handkerchiefs and the lawn, which were pawned on the 19th and 22nd of December, I believe, by the prisoner Jemima Bell.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390408-name-1660" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1660" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1660" type="surname" value="OVENDEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-1660" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT OVENDEN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable L</hi> 90.) I attended the examination of the prisoners—I saw them sign this examination—(<hi rend="italic">read</hi>)—"Jemima Bell says, I remember pledging the black silk handkerchiefs; my father gave them to me, and told me to pledge them. The man says, My daughter acted under my direction."</p>
               <p>
